---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
import { href } from '../lib/url';

const myths = [
  {
    claim: '“Floor sitting strengthens your core.”',
    verdict:
      'Unsupported sitting raises low-level muscle activation, but activation is not training. Strength needs load near failure — which sitting never approaches.',
  },
  {
    claim: '“Sitting on the floor gives you myofascial release.”',
    verdict:
      'There is no research on this at all. Fascia is real; the idea that resting on the ground “releases” it borrows credibility from the (already thin) foam-rolling literature.',
  },
  {
    claim: '“Floor sitting fixes your posture and back pain.”',
    verdict:
      'A review of reviews found no consensus that any posture causes back pain. Oddly, slumped sitting was the lowest-pressure posture in the best in-vivo disc study.',
  },
  {
    claim: '“Standing desks burn serious calories.”',
    verdict:
      'Standing beats sitting by about 9 kcal an hour. Real, but small. The energy that matters is in the transitions — getting up and down — not in holding still while upright.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Why live low"
  description="The honest case for floor living: the Sitting–Rising Test and mortality, mobility you use or lose, the knee caveat, and the myths we refuse to repeat."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="The evidence, honestly"
    title="Why live low"
    lede="The case for floor living is strong enough to make plainly and nuanced enough to keep interesting. Here it is with the caveats left in — because a claim you can trust is worth more than one that sounds good."
  />

  <div class="mx-auto mt-16 max-w-3xl space-y-20 px-5 pb-8 sm:px-8">
    <!-- SRT -->
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="eyebrow text-sagedeep">The one test worth taking</p>
      <h2 class="display-3 font-display text-ink">Can you get off the floor?</h2>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        In a Brazilian study of 2,002 adults aged 51–80, researchers scored how
        people lowered to the floor and stood back up — ten points, minus one for
        each hand, knee, or support used. Over about six years, each single point
        of a better score came with roughly <strong class="text-ink">21% better
        survival</strong>, and the lowest scorers died at five to six times the
        rate of the highest.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        A larger 2025 follow-up of 4,282 people tracked for a median of twelve
        years found the same shape, more starkly: a perfect ten carried about a
        <strong class="text-ink">3.7% death rate</strong>, versus
        <strong class="text-ink">42%</strong> for the lowest scorers.
      </p>
      <Callout variant="caution" title="The honest reading">
        The Sitting–Rising Test measures <strong>musculoskeletal fitness</strong> —
        strength, flexibility, balance, leanness. Its link to lifespan is a real
        <em>association</em>, not proof that the habit of floor-sitting adds years.
        Fit people both score well <em>and</em> live longer. It is a superb
        starting line and a lousy fortune-teller.
        <span class="mt-1 block text-xs text-inkmuted">
          Sources: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23242910/">de Brito et al., 2012/2014</a> ·
          <a href="https://academic.oup.com/eurjpc/advance-article/doi/10.1093/eurjpc/zwaf325/8163161">Araújo et al., 2025</a>.
        </span>
      </Callout>
    </section>

    <!-- Mobility -->
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="eyebrow text-sagedeep">Range you keep</p>
      <h2 class="display-3 font-display text-ink">Use it, or slowly lose it</h2>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        A full resting squat asks for around 35° of ankle bend and deep hip
        flexion. Most Western adults can't find it — not because of anatomy, but
        because a life of chairs never asks for the range, so the calf and hips
        quietly tighten. Populations that still sit on the floor keep markedly
        more hip rotation and flexion into old age.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        The point isn't that the floor magically stretches you. It's that
        chairs let you live in a narrow slice of your available movement, and the
        floor gently insists on the rest of it.
      </p>
      <Callout variant="evidence">
        Strongest where it's descriptive: floor postures <em>demand</em> large
        hip and ankle range, and habitual floor-sitters <em>have</em> more of it.
        Whether the habit <em>builds</em> that range hasn't been proven in a
        trial — it's plausible, not settled. Targeted mobility work, at least,
        clearly does increase ankle range.
      </Callout>
    </section>

    <!-- Knee caveat -->
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="eyebrow text-sagedeep">The nuance everyone skips</p>
      <h2 class="display-3 font-display text-ink">Kind to hips, a risk to knees</h2>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        Here's the caveat the wellness internet leaves out. Populations that
        squat and kneel for hours a day show <em>strikingly low</em> hip
        arthritis — but <em>more</em> knee osteoarthritis. In the Beijing
        Osteoarthritis Study, hours of daily squatting roughly doubled the odds
        of knee OA.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        So we don't preach marathon squat-holds. We preach <strong class="text-ink">variety,
        moderation, and pain-free range</strong>: many short visits to many
        positions, not one punishing posture held for an hour.
      </p>
      <Callout variant="caution" title="If your joints have history">
        Deep flexion is the thing to modify with knee or hip osteoarthritis,
        after a joint replacement (cross-legged and deep squatting are classic
        early no-gos), or in pregnancy (loose ligaments). Prop generously, stay
        pain-free, and check with a professional. See <a href={href('/start')}>how to start</a>.
      </Callout>
    </section>

    <!-- Up and down -->
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="eyebrow text-sagedeep">The real mechanism</p>
      <h2 class="display-3 font-display text-ink">The magic is in the transitions</h2>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        A room without chairs makes you get up and down dozens of times a day.
        Each rise from the floor is an unscheduled squat. This is where floor
        living most plausibly earns its keep — not in the sitting, but in the
        endless, low-grade, get-up-and-do-it-again movement it forces.
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        It rhymes with what we know: breaking up long sitting improves blood
        sugar and circulation, and it's the <em>interruptions</em> that help, not
        the posture you interrupt it with. The floor is simply a very good excuse
        to keep moving.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Myths -->
    <section class="space-y-6">
      <p class="eyebrow text-sagedeep">Myths vs evidence</p>
      <h2 class="display-3 font-display text-ink">Four claims we won't repeat</h2>
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-inksoft">
        Being honest about what floor living <em>doesn't</em> do is how we earn
        the right to tell you what it does.
      </p>
      <div class="grid gap-4">
        {
          myths.map((m) => (
            <div class="rounded-soft border border-line bg-sand/40 p-5">
              <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink">{m.claim}</p>
              <p class="mt-2 text-[0.95rem] leading-relaxed text-inksoft">{m.verdict}</p>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Bottom line -->
    <section class="rounded-soft bg-ink px-6 py-10 text-paper sm:px-10">
      <p class="eyebrow text-straw">The bottom line</p>
      <p class="mt-3 font-display text-2xl leading-snug sm:text-3xl">
        Variety and movement beat any single “correct” posture. Floor living's
        real gift is that it keeps putting you on the ground and asking you to get
        back up.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href={href('/start')} class="rounded-pill bg-paper px-5 py-2.5 font-semibold text-ink no-underline">How to start</a>
        <a href={href('/spaces')} class="rounded-pill border border-paper/40 px-5 py-2.5 font-semibold text-paper no-underline">Set up your space</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
